ns/pi_thumbsup.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: faith healing</span><hr size=1> Actually, Alek, I think you totally missed my point!  I'll try again, though.  And I haven't said how I feel one way or the other about the possibility of faith healing, so I won't even address how you imagine I would respond to your postulations b/c that would clog things up as far as the point I was making.<br>
<br>
Basically, I was saying your analogy comparing faith healing to the placebo effect was not apt in at least one way.<br>
<br>
When people experience the placebo effect, they think they are getting something that they are not (for instance they think they are given a magic stone that gives them the power to do addition, when in fact, it is just a regular stone from the garden).  But their faith in the idea that the stone is magic allows them the confidence to ace their math exam.<br>
<br>
But I was merely arguing that those who believe in faith healing may believe that by praying *for others who are not even aware that prayers were being said for them* may think that a miracle can still occur *unbeknownst* to the recipient.<br>
<br>
Basically, the placebo effect's recipient is tricked into thinking that they are given something that they aren't.  You could say the same thing for a person who actively sought out a faith healer, or asked people to pray for healing with the desired result  <br>
<br>
The hole is, when folks are the unaware recipients of prayer, they are not being tricked.  They may later learn that prayers were said and link that to explain an unexplained recovery, but that is not the same thing as a placebo effect.<br>
<br>
--Beth<br>
